Extreme Panic
Copenhagen - As we often hear, we know how the end of the world will come, usually it's the ecological collapse.
Actually, since the Club of Rome published the origin of revelation "The Limits to Growth" over 40 years ago, its basic idea has always accompanied us.
But time is not lenient.
"The Limits to Growth" warned humans in 1972 that catastrophic collapse is at our fingertips.
However, we saw financial panic afterwards, but there was no real shortage or production collapse.
On the contrary, the resources created by human genius were more than sufficient to meet human consumption.
However, the basic idea of "The Limits to Growth" still holds true: we continue a trend, entangled in misleading solutions to minor issues, ignoring the big problems and wise solutions.
By the early 1970s, the optimistic mood of technology was over, the Vietnam War became a disaster, and society was plunged into turmoil, with the economy stagnating.
Rachel Carson's book "Silent Spring" in 1962 sparked people's panic about pollution and ignited the modern environmentalist movement; Paul Ehrlich's "Population Bomb" in 1968 explained everything.
However, people were pessimistic on the first Earth Day in 1970.
The intent of "The Limits to Growth" is to worry people about exhausting resources.
This is our fate because too many people want to consume too much.
Even if our genius has won us some time, we will ultimately destroy the earth and ourselves with pollution.
The only hope is to achieve social stability at a significantly lower level of poverty through stagnant economic growth, reduced consumption, recycling, and forcing people to have fewer births.
This viewpoint is still resonating today, despite being entirely wrong.
For example, the authors of "The Limits to Growth" predicted that the world would exhaust aluminium, copper, gold, lead, mercury, molybdenum, natural gas, oil, silver, tin, tungsten, and zinc by 2013.
However, even though commodity prices have recently rebounded, they have overall fallen to one-third of the levels of 150 years ago.
Technological innovation has replaced mercury in batteries, dental fillings, and thermometers; by 2000, mercury consumption had dropped by 98%, and prices had fallen by 90%.
More broadly, since 1946, supplies of copper, aluminium, iron, and zinc have all exceeded demand, thanks to the discovery of new reserves and more economical new extraction technologies.
Similarly, oil and natural gas were originally expected to be depleted in 1990 and 1992 respectively; now their reserves are both higher than 1970 levels, despite a huge increase in our consumption.
In the past six years, shale gas alone has doubled the potential natural gas resources of the US, cutting prices in half.
As for economic collapse, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change estimates that global per capita GDP will increase 14-fold this century, with developing countries increasing 24-fold.
The error of "The Limits to Growth" lies in ignoring the greatest resource of all: our own ingenuity.
Population growth has been decelerating since the 1960s.
Food supply did not collapse (15 billion arable land is being utilized, and there are 27 billion acres in reserve).
Nutritional deficiency rate has been eliminated by more than half, decreasing from 35% of the world's population to 16%.
Pollution did not trouble us either.
The Club of Rome imagined in a pastoral past, we had no suspended particulate air pollution, and all were happy farmers, while in the future, smokestacks from heaters would make it impossible for us to breathe. Reality is exactly the opposite.
By 1900, the global population was only 1.5 billion, and nearly 3 million people - equivalent to one in every 500 - died each year from air pollution, most of which was indoor air pollution.
As for mortality, this ratio has declined to one death per 2000 people.
Although the number of deaths from pollution is still higher than that from malaria, its mortality rate is declining rather than rising.
Despite this, the idea cultivated by "The Limits to Growth" still dominates public and elite thinking.
Take recycling for example, it is usually just a feel-good gesture that costs the environment a lot while having little effect.
For instance, paper is often from sustainable forests rather than tropical rainforests.
Programs and government subsidies for paper recycling result in low-quality paper, protecting resources that are not under threat.
Similarly, the fear of overpopulation has led to self-destructive policies, such as China's family planning and India's forced sterilization.
Furthermore, despite the fact that pesticides and other pollutants were believed to kill half of humanity, good pesticide regulation resulted in only 20 deaths per year in the United States, while the use of pesticides created cheaper and more abundant food supplies.
In fact, relying solely on organic farming — a movement sparked by pesticide hysteria — would impose an additional $100 billion in costs on the United States every year.
Agricultural efficiency would decline by 16%, and to maintain current production, an additional 65 million acres of land would need to be cultivated — half the area of modern California.
Price increases will lead to a decline in consumption of fruits and vegetables, resulting in severe negative health effects (including an increase of tens of thousands of cancer deaths per year).
The obsession with dark scenarios prevents us from paying attention to the real global threat.
Poverty is one of the biggest killers, and easily treatable diseases still cause 15 million deaths per year - a quarter of total deaths.
The solution lies in economic growth.
Once people escape poverty, most can afford to pay for the prevention of infectious diseases.
In the past thirty years, China has lifted 680 million people out of poverty, leading the world in reducing poverty by nearly 1 billion people.
This has brought about a large-scale improvement in health, lifespan, and quality of life.
The forty years of history since the publication of "The Limits to Growth" have shown that we need more, not less, growth.
Trade expansion is estimated to bring over $100 trillion in benefits per year by the end of this century, far surpassing the benefits of the "good feeling" policies driven by fear, which are reluctant and timid.
But this requires abandoning the anti-growth mindset and using our boundless potential to create a brighter future.
